0.body: Simple file system implementation using the 9P protocol froggr is a modern implementation of the Plan 9 filesystem protocol (9P), focusing on providing flexible namespace management through bind operations.
0.title: froggr 🐸

1.body: The 9P protocol is a network protocol developed for the Plan 9 operating system, designed to provide transparent access to resources across a network. One of its key features is the ability to manipulate the namespace through operations like bind.
1.title: What is 9P?

10.body: Froggr implements a 9P filesystem server that: Handles client requests Manages namespace operations Provides filesystem access Maintains session state
10.title: 5. Server-Based Architecture

103.body: Union directories allow you to combine multiple sources into a single view, creating a merged namespace.
103.title: Union Directories

104.body: You can create union directories by using multiple bind operations with different modes. The order of operations matters, as it determines the lookup priority.
104.title: Creating Union Directories

105.body:
frg bind -b /local/bin /bin
frg bind -a /backup/bin /bin This creates a three-layer union: /local/bin (highest priority) Original /bin (middle priority) /backup/bin (lowest priority)
105.title: Basic Example

107.body:
Create a layered development environment: frg bind -b /dev/override /usr
frg bind -a /dev/fallback /usr This allows: Development files to override system files System files to serve as the default Fallback files for missing components
107.title: Development Environment

108.body:
Manage multiple configuration sources: frg bind -b /etc/custom /etc
frg bind -a /etc/defaults /etc This creates a hierarchy where: Custom configurations take precedence System configurations remain as default Default configurations serve as fallback
108.title: Configuration Management

112.body: -v, --verbose: Enable verbose logging -q, --quiet: Suppress all output except errors -h, --help: Show help information
112.title: Options

114.body:
Bind a source directory to a mountpoint. frg bind [OPTIONS] <SOURCE> <MOUNTPOINT> Options -b, --before: Bind source before existing content -a, --after: Bind source after existing content -c, --create: Create mountpoint if it doesn't exist -r, --recursive: Recursively bind subdirectories Examples # Replace binding
frg bind /source /dest # Before binding with mountpoint creation
frg bind -b -c /custom/bin /opt/tools # After binding
frg bind -a /fallback/config /etc

16.body: The bind operation is one of the fundamental mechanisms in Froggr's namespace management system. It allows for dynamic modification of the filesystem view by overlaying directories and files.
16.breadcrumbs: Design Principles » Bind Operations Design » Bind Operation Design
16.title: Bind Operation Design

17.body: Bind Operation Process The bind operation follows a specific process flow: Request Initiation Client sends bind request with source and target paths Bind mode is specified (Replace, Before, After, Create) Validation Source path existence check Target path validation Permission verification Mode-specific requirements check Namespace Update Current namespace state is preserved New binding is created according to specified mode Namespace tree is updated Changes are atomically applied State Management Session state is updated New binding is recorded State is persisted to disk Recovery information is saved Completion Success/failure status is determined Client is notified of result Namespace becomes immediately consistent
17.breadcrumbs: Design Principles » Bind Operations Design » Process Overview
17.title: Process Overview

19.body: All bind operations are atomic Namespace remains consistent during updates Failures result in complete rollback

6.body: Froggr draws heavy inspiration from Plan 9's filesystem architecture, particularly its approach to namespace management. Like Plan 9, Froggr treats everything as a file and uses filesystem operations to manage system resources.

77.body: The P9 protocol for file systems requires a unique feature called bind, which allows for flexible control over the namespace (file hierarchy). The bind operation maps a file, directory, or another namespace tree into a new location in the namespace.
77.title: Bind Operations

78.body: froggr supports four binding modes: Replace Mode : Replace existing content Before Mode : Add content with higher priority After Mode : Add content with lower priority Create Mode : Create mountpoint if needed Each mode provides different behaviors for resolving file lookups when multiple resources are mapped to the same namespace.
78.title: Available Modes

79.body: The Replace mode is the default binding mode in froggr. It completely replaces whatever was previously mounted at the mountpoint with the new source.
79.breadcrumbs: Bind Operations » Replace Mode » Replace Mode
79.title: Replace Mode

8.body: Following Plan 9's union mount concept, Froggr allows multiple directories to be combined into a single view. This enables: Layered filesystem composition Dynamic content aggregation Flexible resource organization
8.title: 3. Union Directories

81.body: The src completely overrides any existing content at the mountpoint. After the bind operation, only the contents of src will be visible at the specified mountpoint.
81.title: Behavior

83.body: Temporarily replace a default configuration directory with a test version: frg bind /test/config /etc After this command, processes will see /test/config contents instead of the original /etc.
83.breadcrumbs: Bind Operations » Replace Mode » Replacing Configuration Directory
83.title: Replacing Configuration Directory

84.body: Redirect access to /bin to a custom toolchain directory for development: frg bind /custom/tools/bin /bin This replaces the system binaries with your custom tools.
84.breadcrumbs: Bind Operations » Replace Mode » Custom Toolchain
84.title: Custom Toolchain

85.body: The Before mode places the new source before the existing contents of the mountpoint in the lookup order.
85.breadcrumbs: Bind Operations » Before Mode » Before Mode
85.title: Before Mode

87.body: When a lookup occurs, froggr searches src first, and if the file isn't found there, it searches the original mountpoint. This creates a layered view where new content takes precedence over existing content.
87.title: Behavior

89.body: Add custom binaries that take precedence over system binaries: frg bind -b /custom/bin /bin In this case, /custom/bin/ls will be used instead of /bin/ls if both exist, while other commands will fall back to /bin.
89.breadcrumbs: Bind Operations » Before Mode » Custom Binary Directory
89.title: Custom Binary Directory

9.body: Bind operations are fundamental to Froggr's namespace manipulation: Replace: Complete replacement of target content Before: Prepend content to existing view After: Append content to existing view Create: Create new bindings for non-existent paths
9.title: 4. Bind Operations

90.body: Prioritize development versions of libraries: frg bind -b /dev/libs /usr/lib This allows testing new library versions while maintaining access to the system libraries as fallback.
90.breadcrumbs: Bind Operations » Before Mode » Development Libraries
90.title: Development Libraries

91.body: The After mode appends the new source to the mountpoint's search path, making it a fallback option.
91.breadcrumbs: Bind Operations » After Mode » After Mode
91.title: After Mode

93.body: froggr resolves lookups by searching the original mountpoint first, and if the file isn't found there, it checks the src. This maintains existing content's priority while providing additional fallback options.
93.title: Behavior

95.body: Add extra fonts while maintaining system defaults: frg bind -a /extra/fonts /fonts System fonts remain the primary source, with additional fonts available when needed.
95.breadcrumbs: Bind Operations » After Mode » Additional Fonts
95.title: Additional Fonts

96.body: Add supplementary configuration files: frg bind -a /additional/config /etc This ensures /etc retains its default behavior but gains additional configuration files when defaults don't exist.
96.breadcrumbs: Bind Operations » After Mode » Configuration Extensions
96.title: Configuration Extensions

97.body: The Create mode ensures the mountpoint exists before performing the bind operation.
97.breadcrumbs: Bind Operations » Create Mode » Create Mode
97.title: Create Mode

99.body: Before performing the bind operation, froggr checks if the mountpoint exists. If it doesn't, the directory is created automatically. After creation (if needed), it performs a standard replace binding.
99.title: Behavior
